      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you've hit on a crucial detail! Yes, the machine's value does indeed \"disappear\" (or rather, depreciate) every year until it hits that 5,000 salvage value mark. In accounting, we track this loss of value using a **Depreciation Expense** entry in your ledger, paired with a **Accumulated Depreciation** contra-asset account.\n\nHere is how the ledger looks for your machine:\n\n*   **Asset Account:** You start with a debit of **50,000** (the original cost).\n*   **Accumulated Depreciation Account:** You credit this account for each year's expense. By the end of Year 5, this account will hold a total credit of **45,000** (9,000 x 5 years).\n*   **Net Book Value:** When you calculate the book value, you subtract the Accumulated Depreciation from the original cost. So, after 5 years, your ledger shows: 50,000 (Cost) - 45,000 (Accumulated Depreciation) = **5,000**",
